# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: volumetric-rendering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] An **isosurface** is a three-dimensional analog of an isoline.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] It is a surface that represents points of a constant value (e.g. pressure, temperature, velocity, density) within a volume of space; in other words, it is a level set of a continuous function whose domain is 3-space.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] The term *isoline* is also sometimes used for domains of more than 3 dimensions.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] Isosurfaces are normally displayed using computer graphics, and are used as data visualization methods in computational fluid dynamics (CFD), allowing engineers to study features of a fluid flow (gas or liquid) around objects, such as aircraft wings.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] An isosurface may represent an individual shock wave in supersonic flight, or several isosurfaces may be generated showing a sequence of pressure values in the air flowing around a wing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] Isosurfaces tend to be a popular form of visualization for volume datasets since they can be rendered by a simple polygonal model, which can be drawn on the screen very quickly.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] In medical imaging, isosurfaces may be used to represent regions of a particular density in a three-dimensional CT scan, allowing the visualization of internal organs, bones, or other structures.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] Numerous other disciplines that are interested in three-dimensional data often use isosurfaces to obtain information about pharmacology, chemistry, geophysics and meteorology.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] The marching cubes algorithm was first published in the 1987 SIGGRAPH proceedings by Lorensen and Cline, and it creates a surface by intersecting the edges of a data volume grid with the volume contour.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] Where the surface intersects the edge the algorithm creates a vertex.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] By using a table of different triangles depending on different patterns of edge intersections the algorithm can create a surface.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] This algorithm has solutions for implementation both on the CPU and on the GPU.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] The asymptotic decider algorithm was developed as an extension to marching cubes in order to resolve the possibility of ambiguity in it.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] The marching tetrahedra algorithm was developed as an extension to marching cubes in order to solve an ambiguity in that algorithm and to create higher quality output surface.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] The Surface Nets algorithm places an intersecting vertex in the middle of a volume voxel instead of at the edges, leading to a smoother output surface.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] The dual contouring algorithm was first published in the 2002 SIGGRAPH proceedings by Ju and Losasso, developed as an extension to both surface nets and marching cubes.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] It retains a dual vertex within the voxel but no longer at the center.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] Dual contouring leverages the position and normal of where the surface crosses the edges of a voxel to interpolate the position of the dual vertex within the voxel.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] This has the benefit of retaining sharp or smooth surfaces where surface nets often look blocky or incorrectly beveled.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] Dual contouring often uses surface generation that leverages octrees as an optimization to adapt the number of triangles in output to the complexity of the surface.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] Examples of isosurfaces are 'Metaballs' or 'blobby objects' used in 3D visualisation.
[src:volumetric-rendering/isosurface] A more general way to construct an isosurface is to use the function representation.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] The fundamental quantity that describes a field of radiation is called **spectral radiance** in radiometric terms (in other fields it is often called **specific intensity**).
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] For a very small area element in the radiation field, there can be electromagnetic radiation passing in both senses in every spatial direction through it.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] where $\theta$ is the angle that the unit direction vector ${\hat {\mathbf {n} }}$ makes with a normal to the area element.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] The units of the spectral radiance are seen to be energy/time/area/solid angle/frequency.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] In MKS units this would be W·m−2·sr−1·Hz−1 (watts per square-metre-steradian-hertz).
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] The equation of radiative transfer simply says that as a beam of radiation travels, it loses energy to absorption, gains energy by emission processes, and redistributes energy by scattering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] Solutions to the equation of radiative transfer form an enormous body of work.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] The differences however, are essentially due to the various forms for the emission and absorption coefficients.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] A particularly useful simplification of the equation of radiative transfer occurs under the conditions of local thermodynamic equilibrium (LTE).
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] Local equilibrium may apply only to a certain subset of particles in the system.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] For example, LTE is usually applied only to massive particles.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] In a radiating gas, the photons being emitted and absorbed by the gas do not need to be in a thermodynamic equilibrium with each other or with the massive particles of the gas in order for LTE to exist.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] In this situation, the absorbing/emitting medium consists of massive particles which are locally in equilibrium with each other, and therefore have a definable temperature (Zeroth Law of Thermodynamics).
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] The radiation field is not, however in equilibrium and is being entirely driven by the presence of the massive particles.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] where $B_{\nu }(T)$ is the black body spectral radiance at temperature T.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] Knowing the temperature profile and the density profile of the medium is sufficient to calculate a solution to the equation of radiative transfer.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] The Eddington approximation is distinct from the two-stream approximation.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] The two-stream approximation assumes that the intensity is constant with angle in the upward hemisphere, with a different constant value in the downward hemisphere.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] $I_{\nu }(\mu ,z)=a(z)+\mu b(z)$ where z is the normal direction to the slab-like medium.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] Note that expressing angular integrals in terms of $\mu$ simplifies things because $d\mu =-\sin \theta \,d\theta$ appears in the Jacobian of integrals in spherical coordinates.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] The Eddington approximation can be used to obtain the spectral radiance in a "plane-parallel" medium (one in which properties only vary in the perpendicular direction) with isotropic frequency-independent scattering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] Thus the Eddington approximation is equivalent to setting ${\textstyle K_{\nu }={\frac {1}{3}}J_{\nu }}$ .
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] Higher order versions of the Eddington approximation also exist, and consist of more complicated linear relations of the intensity moments.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] This extra equation can be used as a closure relation for the truncated system of moments.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] Note that the first two moments have simple physical meanings. $J_{\nu }$ is the isotropic intensity at a point, and $H_{\nu }$ is the flux through that point in the z direction.
[src:volumetric-rendering/radiative-transfer] This equation shows how the effective optical depth in scattering-dominated systems may be significantly different from that given by the scattering opacity if the absorptive opacity is small.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The term "Ray Casting" was introduced by Scott Roth while at the General Motors Research Labs from 1978–1980.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] His paper, "Ray Casting for Modeling Solids", describes modeled solid objects by combining primitive solids, such as blocks and cylinders, using the set operators union (+), intersection (&), and difference (−).
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The general idea of using these binary operators for solid modeling is largely due to Voelcker and Requicha's geometric modelling group at the University of Rochester.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Before ray casting (and ray tracing), computer graphics algorithms projected surfaces or edges (e.g., lines) from the 3D world to the image plane where visibility logic had to be applied.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The world-to-image plane projection is a 3D homogeneous coordinate system transformation, also known as 3D projection, affine transformation, or projective transform (homography).
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Rendering an image this way is difficult to achieve with hidden surface/edge removal.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Plus, silhouettes of curved surfaces have to be explicitly solved for whereas it is an implicit by-product of ray casting, so there is no need to explicitly solve for it whenever the view changes.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Ray casting greatly simplified image rendering of 3D objects and scenes because a line transforms to a line.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] So, instead of projecting curved edges and surfaces in the 3D scene to the 2D image plane, transformed lines (rays) are intersected with the objects in the scene.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] A homogeneous coordinate transformation is represented by a 4×4 matrix.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The mathematical technique is common to computer graphics and geometric modeling.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] A transform includes rotations around the three axes, independent scaling along the axes, translations in 3D, and even skewing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Transforms are easily concatenated via matrix arithmetic.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] For use with a 4×4 matrix, a point is represented by [*X*, *Y*, *Z*, 1], and a direction vector is represented by [*Dx*, *Dy*, *Dz*, 0].
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Ray casting is the most basic of many computer graphics rendering algorithms that use the geometric algorithm of ray tracing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Ray tracing-based rendering algorithms operate in image order to render three-dimensional scenes to two-dimensional images.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Geometric rays are traced from the eye of the observer to sample the light (radiance) travelling toward the observer from the ray direction.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The speed and simplicity of ray casting comes from computing the color of the light without recursively tracing additional rays that sample the radiance incident on the point that the ray hit.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This eliminates the possibility of accurately rendering reflections, refractions, or the natural falloff of shadows; however all of these elements can be faked to a degree, by creative use of texture maps or other methods.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The high speed of calculation made ray casting a handy rendering method in early real-time 3D video games.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The idea behind ray casting is to trace rays from the eye, one per pixel, and find the closest object blocking the path of that ray—think of an image as a screen-door, with each square in the screen being a pixel.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This is then the object the eye sees through that pixel.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Using the material properties and the effect of the lights in the scene, this algorithm can determine the shading of this object.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The simplifying assumption is made that if a surface faces a light, the light will reach that surface and not be blocked or in shadow.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The shading of the surface is computed using traditional 3D computer graphics shading models.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] One important advantage ray casting offered over older scanline algorithms was its ability to easily deal with non-planar surfaces and solids, such as cones and spheres.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] If a mathematical surface can be intersected by a ray, it can be rendered using ray casting.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Elaborate objects can be created by using solid modelling techniques and easily rendered.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Light rays and the camera geometry form the basis for all geometric reasoning here.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This figure shows a pinhole camera model for perspective effect in image processing and a parallel camera model for mass analysis.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The simple pinhole camera model consists of a focal point (or eye point) and a square pixel array (or screen).
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Straight light rays pass through the pixel array to connect the focal point with the scene, one ray per pixel.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] To shade pictures, the rays’ intensities are measured and stored as pixels.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The reflecting surface responsible for a pixel’s value intersects the pixel’s ray.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] When the focal length, distance between focal point and screen, is infinite, then the view is called “parallel” because all light rays are parallel to each other, perpendicular to the screen.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Although the perspective view is natural for making pictures, some applications need rays that can be uniformly distributed in space.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] For modeling convenience, a typical standard coordinate system for the camera has the screen in the X–Y plane, the scene in the +Z half space, and the focal point on the −Z axis.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] A *ray* is simply a straight line in the 3D space of the camera model.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] It is best defined in parameterized form as a point vector (*X*0, *Y*0, *Z*0) and a direction vector (*Dx*, *Dy*, *Dz*).
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] In this form, points on the line are ordered and accessed via a single parameter t.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] If the vector is normalized, then the parameter t is distance along the line.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Where n is the number of ray-surface intersections.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The ordered list of ray parameters, *t* [*i*], denote the enter–exit points.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The ray enters a solid at point *t* [1], exits at *t* [2], enters a solid at *t* [3], etc.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Point *t* [1] is closest to the camera and *t* [*n*] is furthest.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] In association with the ray parameters, the surface pointers contain a unique address for the intersected surface’s information.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The surface can have various properties such as color, specularity, transparency with/without refraction, translucency, etc.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The solid associated with the surface may have its own physical properties such as density.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This could be useful, for instance, when an object consists of an assembly of different materials and the overall center of mass and moments of inertia are of interest.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Three algorithms using ray casting are to make line drawings, to make shaded pictures, and to compute volumes and other physical properties.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Each algorithm, given a camera model, casts one ray per pixel in the screen.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] For computing volume, the resolution of the pixel screen to use depends on the desired accuracy of the solution.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] For line drawings and picture shading, the resolution determines the quality of the image.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] To draw the visible edges of a solid, generate one ray per pixel moving top-down, left-right in the screen.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Evaluate each ray in order to identify the visible surface *S* [1], the first surface pointer in the sorted list of ray-surface intersections.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] If the visible surface at pixel location (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X* − 1, *Y* ), then display a vertical line one pixel long centered at (*X* − ½, *Y* ).
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Similarly, if the visible surface at (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X*, *Y* − 1), then display a horizontal line one pixel long centered at (*X*, *Y* − ½).
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The resulting drawing will consist of horizontal and vertical edges only, looking jagged in coarse resolutions.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Roth’s ray casting system generated the images of solid objects on the right.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Box enclosures, dynamic bounding, and coherence were used for optimization.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] For each picture, the screen was sampled with a density of about 100×100 (i.e., 10,000) rays and new edges were located via binary searches.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Then all edges were followed by casting additional rays at one pixel increments on the two sides of the edges.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Each picture was drawn on a Tektronix tube at 780×780 resolution.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] To make a shaded picture, again cast one ray per pixel in the screen.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This time, however, use the visible surface pointer S[1] at each pixel to access the description of the surface.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] From this, compute the surface normal at the visible point *t* [1].
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The pixel’s value, the displayable light intensity, is proportional to the cosine of the angle formed by the surface normal and the light-source-to-surface vector.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Processing all pixels this way produces a raster-type picture of the scene.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The volume (and similar properties) of a solid bounded by curved surfaces is easily computed by the “approximating sums” integration method, by approximating the solid with a set of rectangular parallelepipeds.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This is accomplished by taking an “in-depth” picture of the solid in a parallel view.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Casting rays through the screen into the solid partitions the solid into volume elements.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Two dimensions of the parallelepipeds are constant, defined by the 2D spacing of rays in the screen.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The third dimension is variable, defined by the enter–exit point computed.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] where L is defined as the length of the direction vector.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Each ${\tfrac {t[i]\ -\ t[i-1]}{L}}$ is a length of a ray segment that is inside of the solid.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This figure shows the parallelepipeds for a modeled solid using ray casting.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This is a use of parallel-projection camera model.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This figure shows an example of the binary operators in a composition tree using “+” and “−” where a single ray is evaluated.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The ray casting procedure starts at the top of the solid composition tree, recursively descends to the bottom, classifies the ray with respect to the primitive solids, and then returns up the tree combining the classifications of the left and right subtrees.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This figure illustrates the combining of the left and right classifications for all three binary operators.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Ray casting is a natural modeling tool for making shaded pictures.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The grayscale ray-casting system developed by Scott Roth and Daniel Bass at GM Research Labs produced pictures on a Ramtek color raster display around 1979.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This figure shows a table scene with shadows from two point light sources.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Shading algorithms that implement all of the realistic effects are computationally expensive, but relatively simple.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] For example, the following figure shows the additional rays that could be cast for a single light source.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] For a single pixel in the image to be rendered, the algorithm casts a ray starting at the focal point and determines that it intersects a semi-transparent rectangle and a shiny circle.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] An additional ray must then be cast starting at that point in the direction symmetrically opposite the surface normal at the ray-surface intersection point in order to determine what is visible in the mirrored reflection.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] That ray intersects the triangle which is opaque.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Finally, each ray-surface intersection point is tested to determine if it is in shadow.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The “Shadow feeler” ray is cast from the ray-surface intersection point to the light source to determine if any other surface blocks that pathway.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The secondary ray is then processed as a specular ray.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] For the refraction formula and pictorial examples, see Whitted’s paper.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Ray casting qualifies as a brute force method for solving problems.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The minimal algorithm is simple, particularly in consideration of its many applications and ease of use, but applications typically cast many rays.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Millions of rays may be cast to render a single frame of an animated film.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Computer processing time increases with the resolution of the screen and the number of primitive solids/surfaces in the composition.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] By using minimum bounding boxes around the solids in the composition tree, the exhaustive search for a ray-solid intersection resembles an efficient binary search.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The brute force algorithm does an exhaustive search because it always visits all the nodes in the tree—transforming the ray into primitives’ local coordinate systems, testing for ray-surface intersections, and combining the classifications—even when the ray clearly misses the solid.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] In order to detect a “clear miss”, a faster algorithm uses the binary composition tree as a hierarchical representation of the space that the solid composition occupies.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] But all position, shape, and size information is stored at the leaves of the tree where primitive solids reside.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The top and intermediate nodes in the tree only specify combine operators.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Characterizing with enclosures the space that all solids fill gives all nodes in the tree an abstract summary of position and size information.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Then, the quick “ray intersects enclosure” tests guide the search in the hierarchy.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] When the test fails at an intermediate node in the tree, the ray is guaranteed to classify as out of the composite, so recursing down its subtrees to further investigate is unnecessary.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Accurately assessing the cost savings for using enclosures is difficult because it depends on the spatial distribution of the primitives (the complexity distribution) and on the organization of the composition tree.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The following are miscellaneous performance improvements made in Roth’s paper on ray casting, but there have been considerable improvements subsequently made by others.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] If the operator at a composite node in the tree is − or & and the ray classifies as out of the composite’s left sub-solid, then the ray will classify as out of the composite regardless of the ray’s classification with respect to the right sub-solid.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] So, classifying the ray with respect to the right sub-solid is unnecessary and should be avoided for efficiency.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] By initially combining the screen-to-scene transform with the primitive’s scene-to-local transform and storing the resulting screen-to-local transforms in the primitive’s data structures, one ray transform per ray-surface intersection is eliminated.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Given a deep composition tree, recursion can be expensive in combination with allocating and freeing up memory.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Recursion can be simulated using static arrays as stacks.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] If only the visible edges of the solid are to be displayed, the ray casting algorithm can dynamically bound the ray to cut off the search.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] That is, after finding that a ray intersects a sub-solid, the algorithm can use the intersection point closest to the screen to tighten the depth bound for the “ray intersections box” test.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This only works for the + part of the tree, starting at the top.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] With – and &, nearby “in” parts of the ray may later become “out”.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The principle of coherence is that the surfaces visible at two neighboring pixels are more likely to be the same than different.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Developers of computer graphics and vision systems have applied this empirical truth for efficiency and performance.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] For line drawings, the image area containing edges is normally much less than the total image area, so ray casting should be concentrated around the edges and not in the open regions.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This can be effectively implemented by sparsely sampling the screen with rays and then locating, when neighboring rays identify different visible surfaces, the edges via binary searches.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The jagged edges caused by aliasing is an undesirable effect of point sampling techniques and is a classic problem with raster display algorithms.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Linear or smoothly curved edges will appear jagged and are particularly objectionable in animations because movement of the image makes the edges appear fuzzy or look like little moving escalators.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Also, details in the scene smaller than the spacing between rays may be lost.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The jagged edges in a line drawing can be smoothed by edge following.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The purpose of such an algorithm is to minimize the number of lines needed to draw the picture within one pixel accuracy.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The line drawings above were drawn this way.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] To smooth the jagged edges in a shaded picture with subpixel accuracy, additional rays should be cast for information about the edges.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] (See Supersampling for a general approach.) Edges are formed by the intersection of surfaces or by the profile of a curved surface.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Applying "Coherence" as described above via binary search, if the visible surface at pixel (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X* + 1, *Y* ), then a ray could be generated midway between them at (*X* + ½, *Y* ) and the visible surface there identified.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The distance between sample points could be further subdivided, but the search need not be deep.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The primary search depth to smooth jagged edges is a function of the intensity gradient across the edge.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] For the history of ray casting, see Ray tracing (graphics) as both are essentially the same technique under different names.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Scott Roth had invented the term "ray casting" before having heard of "ray tracing".
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Additionally, Scott Roth's development of ray casting at GM Research Labs occurred concurrently with Turner Whitted's ray tracing work at Bell Labs.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] In early first person games, raycasting was used to efficiently render a 3D world from a 2D playing field using a simple one-dimensional scan over the horizontal width of the screen.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Early first-person shooters used 2D ray casting as a technique to create a 3D effect from a 2D world.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] While the world appears 3D, the player cannot look up or down or only in limited angles with shearing distortion.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This style of rendering eliminates the need to fire a ray for each pixel in the frame as is the case with modern engines; once the hit point is found the projection distortion is applied to the surface texture and an entire vertical column is copied from the result into the frame.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] This style of rendering also imposes limitations on the type of rendering which can be performed, for example **depth sorting** but depth buffering may not.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] That is polygons must be full in front of or behind one another, they may not partially overlap or intersect.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The video game *Wolfenstein 3D* was built from a square based grid of uniform height walls meeting solid-colored floors and ceilings.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] In order to draw the world, a single ray was traced for every column of screen pixels and a vertical slice of wall texture was selected and scaled according to where in the world the ray hits a wall and how far it travels before doing so.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The purpose of the grid based levels was twofold — ray-wall collisions can be found more quickly since the potential hits become more predictable and memory overhead is reduced.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] However, encoding wide-open areas takes extra space.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The Raven Software game *ShadowCaster* uses an improved Wolfenstein-based engine with added floors and ceilings texturing and variable wall heights.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The Voxel Space engine developed by NovaLogic for the *Comanche* games traced a ray through each column of screen pixels and tested each ray against points in a heightmap.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Then it transformed each element of the heightmap into a column of pixels, determined which are visible (that is, have not been occluded by pixels that have been drawn in front), and drew them with the corresponding color from the texture map.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] Later DOS games like *id Software's DOOM* kept many of the raycasting 2.5D restrictions for speed but went on to switch to alternative rendering techniques (like BSP), making them no longer raycasting engines.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] The problem has been investigated for various settings: space dimension, types of objects, restrictions on query rays, etc.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-casting] One technique is to use a sparse voxel octree.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] The technique dates back to at least the 1980s; the 1989 paper "Hypertexture" by Ken Perlin contains an early example of a ray marching method.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] In **sphere tracing**, or **sphere-assisted ray marching** an intersection point is approximated between the ray and a surface defined by a signed distance function (SDF).
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] The SDF is evaluated for each iteration in order to be able take as large steps as possible without missing any part of the surface.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] A threshold is used to cancel further iteration when a point has reached that is close enough to the surface.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] As powerful GPU hardware became more widely available, this method was popularized by the demoscene and Inigo Quilez, co-creator of Shadertoy.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] For simple scenes with basic 3D shapes, ray marching does not have many benefits over ray tracing (which finds intersections without marching through the space).
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] Strengths of SDF ray marching are, for example, when morphing shapes, approximating soft shadows, repetition of geometry, and algorithmically defined scenes.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] Signed distance functions exist for many primitive 3D shapes.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] They can be combined using mathematical operations like modulo and booleans to form more complex surfaces.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] For instance, taking the modulus of an SDF's input coordinates tiles its volume across all of space, and taking the maximum of two SDFs gives their volumes' surface of intersection.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] Because SDFs can be defined for many fractals, sphere tracing is often used for 3D fractal rendering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] A similar technique to sphere-assisted ray marching, the use of cubes and taxicab distance can be used to render voxel volumes.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] In volumetric ray marching, each ray is traced so that color and/or density can be sampled along the ray and then be combined into a final pixel color.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] This is often used for example when rendering clouds or 3D medical scans.
[src:volumetric-rendering/ray-marching] When rendering screen space effects, such as screen space reflection (SSR) and screen space shadows, rays are traced using G-buffers, where depth and surface normal data is stored per each 2D pixel.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In a computer graphics context, in standard usage, the word "rendering" by itself means rendering 3D scenes, but it is sometimes used with a broader meaning.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A modifier such as "2D" or "3D" is used when there is potential ambiguity (e.g.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A software application or component that performs rendering is called a **rendering engine**, **render engine**, **rendering system**, **graphics engine**, or simply a **renderer**.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A distinction is made between real-time rendering, in which images are generated and displayed immediately (ideally fast enough to give the impression of motion or animation), and offline rendering (sometimes called pre-rendering) in which images or film frames, are generated for later viewing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Offline rendering can use a slower and higher-quality renderer.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Interactive applications such as games must primarily use real-time rendering, although they may incorporate pre-rendered content.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering produces images of scenes or objects defined using coordinates in 3D space, seen from a particular viewpoint.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It uses knowledge and ideas from optics, the study of visual perception, mathematics, and software engineering, and it has applications such as video games, simulators, visual effects for films and television, design visualization, and medical diagnosis.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering requires modeling the propagation of light in an environment, e.g. by applying the rendering equation.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Real-time rendering uses high-performance *rasterization* algorithms that process a list of shapes and determine which pixels are covered by each shape.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When more realism is required (e.g. for architectural visualization or visual effects) slower pixel-by-pixel algorithms such as *ray tracing* are used instead.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (Ray tracing can also be used selectively during rasterized rendering to improve the realism of lighting and reflections.) A type of ray tracing called *path tracing* is currently the most common technique for photorealistic rendering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Path tracing is also popular for generating high-quality non-photorealistic images, such as frames for 3D animated films.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Both rasterization and ray tracing can be sped up ("accelerated") by specially designed microprocessors called GPUs.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rasterization algorithms are also used to produce images containing only 2D shapes such as polygons and text.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] This type of rendering is sometimes called *2D rendering*, and its applications include digital illustration, graphic design, 2D animation, desktop publishing and the display of user interfaces.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, rendering was called **image synthesis** but today this term is likely to mean AI image generation.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The term "neural rendering" is sometimes used when a neural network is the primary means of generating an image but some degree of control over the output image is provided.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks can also assist rendering without replacing traditional algorithms, e.g. by removing noise from path traced images.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A large proportion of computer graphics research has worked towards producing images that resemble photographs.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Fundamental techniques that make this possible were invented in the 1980s, but at the end of the decade, photorealism for complex scenes was still considered a distant goal.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Today, photorealism is routinely achievable for offline rendering, but remains difficult for real-time rendering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In order to produce realistic images, rendering must simulate how light travels from light sources, is reflected, refracted, and scattered (often many times) by objects in the scene, passes through a camera lens, and finally reaches the film or sensor of the camera.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The physics used in these simulations is primarily geometrical optics, in which particles of light follow (usually straight) lines called *rays*, but in some situations (such as when rendering thin films, like the surface of soap bubbles) the wave nature of light must be taken into account.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In realistic scenes, objects are illuminated both by light that arrives directly from a light source (after passing mostly unimpeded through air), and light that has bounced off other objects in the scene.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The simulation of this complex lighting is called global illumination.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In the past, indirect lighting was often faked (especially when rendering animated films) by placing additional hidden lights in the scene, but today path tracing is used to render it accurately.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For true photorealism, the camera used to take the photograph must be simulated.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The *thin lens approximation* allows combining perspective projection with depth of field (and bokeh) emulation.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Camera lens simulations can be made more realistic by modeling the way light is refracted by the components of the lens.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Motion blur is often simulated if film or video frames are being rendered.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Simulated lens flare and bloom are sometimes added to make the image appear subjectively brighter (although the design of real cameras tries to reduce these effects).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering uses mathematical descriptions of how different surface materials reflect light, called *reflectance models* or (when physically plausible) *bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs)*.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering materials such as marble, plant leaves, and human skin requires simulating an effect called subsurface scattering, in which a portion of the light travels into the material, is scattered, and then travels back out again.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The way color, and properties such as roughness, vary over a surface can be represented efficiently using texture mapping.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For some applications (including early stages of 3D modeling), simplified rendering styles such as wireframe rendering may be appropriate, particularly when the material and surface details have not been defined and only the shape of an object is known.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Games and other real-time applications may use simpler and less realistic rendering techniques as an artistic or design choice, or to allow higher frame rates on lower-end hardware.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Orthographic and isometric projections can be used for a stylized effect or to ensure that parallel lines are depicted as parallel in CAD rendering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses techniques like edge detection and posterization to produce 3D images that resemble technical illustrations, cartoons, or other styles of drawing or painting.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In 2D computer graphics the positions and sizes of shapes are specified using 2D coordinates (x and y) instead of 3D coordinates (x, y, and z).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering APIs often use a resolution-independent coordinate system, with a viewport determining how to convert coordinates to pixel indexes called *device coordinates*.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transformations such as scaling, translation, and rotation may be applied before rendering the shapes.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These affine transformations are often represented by 3 × 3 matrices, allowing easier composition of transformations.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Higher-quality 2D rendering engines such as SVG renderers usually implement anti-aliasing to reduce the jagged appearance of rasterized lines and shape edges.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering overlapping shapes, renderers commonly use a "painter's model" in which the shapes are drawn in some determined order, or their contributions to each pixel are composited using blending operations that may depend on the order of the inputs.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers may allow giving shapes a "z index" or "stacking order" to specify the rendering or blending order (unlike the z coordinate used in 3D rendering, this third coordinate only indicates an order, not a distance, and cannot be meaningfully rotated together with the x and y coordinates).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering typically does not simulate light propagation (which would likely require specifying 3D positions or thickness for the shapes).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Effects such as drop shadows and transparency are defined by mathematical functions with no physical basis.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering for print output may need to support very high resolutions, e.g.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 600 or 1200 DPI for a typical laser printer, or 2400 DPI or higher for an imagesetter or platesetter.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Grayscale and color images require halftones (or some form of dithering or stochastic screening) and color separations.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A rendering engine called a *raster image processor* (RIP) converts input data such as PDF files into the high-resolution bitmap images used by the printer.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before a 3D scene or 2D image can be rendered, it must be described in a way that the rendering software can understand.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, inputs for both 2D and 3D rendering were usually text files, which are easier than binary files for humans to edit and debug.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Traditional rendering algorithms use geometric descriptions of 3D scenes or 2D images.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Applications and algorithms that render visualizations of data scanned from the real world, or scientific simulations, may require different types of input data.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The PostScript format (which is often credited with the rise of desktop publishing) provides a standardized, interoperable way to describe 2D graphics and page layout.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) format is also text-based, and the PDF format uses the PostScript language internally.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Many file formats exist for storing individual 3D objects or "models".
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These can be imported into a larger scene, or loaded on-demand by rendering software or games.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A realistic scene may require hundreds of items like household objects, vehicles, and trees, and 3D artists often utilize large libraries of models.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In game production, these models (along with other data such as textures, audio files, and animations) are referred to as "assets".
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scientific and engineering visualization often requires rendering volumetric data generated by 3D scans or simulations.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Perhaps the most common source of such data is medical CT and MRI scans, which need to be rendered for diagnosis.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Volumetric data can be extremely large, and requires specialized data formats to store it efficiently, particularly if the volume is *sparse* (with empty regions that do not contain data).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before rendering, level sets for volumetric data can be extracted and converted into a mesh of triangles, e.g. by using the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms have also been developed that work directly with volumetric data, for example to render realistic depictions of the way light is scattered and absorbed by clouds and smoke, and this type of volumetric rendering is used extensively in visual effects for movies.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering lower-resolution volumetric data without interpolation, the individual cubes or "voxels" may be visible, an effect sometimes used deliberately for game graphics.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photographs of real world objects can be incorporated into a rendered scene by using them as textures for 3D objects.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photos of a scene can also be stitched together to create panoramic images or environment maps, which allow the scene to be rendered very efficiently but only from a single viewpoint.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scanning of real objects and scenes using structured light or lidar produces point clouds consisting of the coordinates of millions of individual points in space, sometimes along with color information.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These point clouds may either be rendered directly or converted into meshes before rendering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A more recent, experimental approach is description of scenes using radiance fields which define the color, intensity, and direction of incoming light at each point in space.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (This is conceptually similar to, but not identical to, the light field recorded by a hologram.) For any useful resolution, the amount of data in a radiance field is so large that it is impractical to represent it directly as volumetric data, and an approximation function must be found.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks are typically used to generate and evaluate these approximations, sometimes using video frames, or a collection of photographs of a scene taken at different angles, as "training data".
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms related to neural networks have recently been used to find approximations of a scene as 3D Gaussians.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The resulting representation is similar to a point cloud, except that it uses fuzzy, partially-transparent blobs of varying dimensions and orientations instead of points.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] As with neural radiance fields, these approximations are often generated from photographs or video frames.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of rendering may be displayed immediately on the screen (many times a second, in the case of real-time rendering such as games) or saved in a raster graphics file format such as JPEG or PNG.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] High-end rendering applications commonly use the OpenEXR file format, which can represent finer gradations of colors and high dynamic range lighting, allowing tone mapping or other adjustments to be applied afterwards without loss of quality.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of a renderer sometimes includes more than just RGB color values.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transparency information can be included, allowing rendered foreground objects to be composited with photographs or video.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It is also sometimes useful to store the contributions of different lights, or of specular and diffuse lighting, as separate channels, so lighting can be adjusted after rendering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The OpenEXR format allows storing many channels of data in a single file.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers such as Blender and Pixar RenderMan support a large variety of configurable values called Arbitrary Output Variables (AOVs).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Choosing how to render a 3D scene usually involves trade-offs between speed, memory usage, and realism (although realism is not always desired).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The **algorithms** developed over the years follow a loose progression, with more advanced methods becoming practical as computing power and memory capacity increased.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Multiple techniques may be used for a single final image.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important distinction is between image order algorithms, which iterate over pixels in the image, and object order algorithms, which iterate over objects in the scene.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For simple scenes, object order is usually more efficient, as there are fewer objects than pixels.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] algorithms that also support filled shapes.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In principle, any 2D vector graphics renderer can be used to render 3D objects by first projecting them onto a 2D image plane.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Different realistic or stylized effects can be obtained by coloring the pixels covered by the objects in different ways.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization is usually synonymous with "object order" rendering (as described above).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It can be used to implement "image order" rendering by casting a ray for each pixel, and finding a corresponding point in the scene.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , requiring a varying number of ray casting operations for each path.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] is usually in the domain of path tracing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] approach that breaks surfaces in the scene into pieces, and estimates the amount of light that each piece receives from light sources, or indirectly from other surfaces.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] of each surface is known, the scene can be rendered using rasterization or ray tracing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , giving ray tracing a rigorous mathematical foundation.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Each of the above approaches has many variations, and there is some overlap.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing may be considered either a distinct technique or a particular type of ray tracing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that the usage of terminology related to ray tracing and path tracing has changed significantly over time.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray marching is a family of algorithms, used by ray casting, for finding intersections between a ray and a complex object, such as a volumetric dataset or a surface defined by a signed distance function.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It is not, by itself, a rendering method, but it can be incorporated into ray tracing and path tracing, and is used by rasterization to implement screen-space reflection and other effects.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A technique called photon mapping traces paths of photons from a light source to an object, accumulating data about irradiance which is then used during conventional ray tracing or path tracing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering a scene using only rays traced from the light source to the camera is impractical, even though it corresponds more closely to reality, because a huge number of photons would need to be simulated, only a tiny fraction of which actually hit the camera.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Some authors call conventional ray tracing "backward" ray tracing because it traces the paths of photons backwards from the camera to the light source, and call following paths from the light source (as in photon mapping) "forward" ray tracing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, sometimes the meaning of these terms is reversed.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Tracing rays starting at the light source can also be called *particle tracing* or *light tracing*, which avoids this ambiguity.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real-time rendering, including video game graphics, typically uses rasterization, but increasingly combines it with ray tracing and path tracing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To enable realistic global illumination, real-time rendering often relies on pre-rendered ("baked") lighting for stationary objects.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For moving objects, it may use a technique called *light probes*, in which lighting is recorded by rendering omnidirectional views of the scene at chosen points in space (often points on a grid to allow easier interpolation).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These are similar to environment maps, but typically use a very low resolution or an approximation such as spherical harmonics.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The term *rasterization* (in a broad sense) encompasses many techniques used for 2D rendering and real-time 3D rendering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] 3D animated films were rendered by rasterization before ray tracing and path tracing became practical.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A renderer combines rasterization with *geometry processing* (which is not specific to rasterization) and *pixel processing* which computes the RGB color values to be placed in the *framebuffer* for display.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, 3D rasterization used algorithms like the *Warnock algorithm* and *scanline rendering* (also called "scan-conversion"), which can handle arbitrary polygons and can rasterize many shapes simultaneously.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Although such algorithms are still important for 2D rendering, 3D rendering now usually divides shapes into triangles and rasterizes them individually using simpler methods.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] High-performance algorithms exist for rasterizing 2D lines, including anti-aliased lines, as well as ellipses and filled triangles.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important special case of 2D rasterization is text rendering, which requires careful anti-aliasing and rounding of coordinates to avoid distorting the letterforms and preserve spacing, density, and sharpness.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After 3D coordinates have been projected onto the image plane, rasterization is primarily a 2D problem, but the 3rd dimension necessitates *hidden surface removal*.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early computer graphics used geometric algorithms or ray casting to remove the hidden portions of shapes, or used the *painter's algorithm*, which sorts shapes by depth (distance from camera) and renders them from back to front.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Depth sorting was later avoided by incorporating depth comparison into the scanline rendering algorithm.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The *z-buffer* algorithm performs the comparisons indirectly by including a depth or "z" value in the framebuffer.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A pixel is only covered by a shape if that shape's z value is lower (indicating closer to the camera) than the z value currently in the buffer.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The z-buffer requires additional memory (an expensive resource at the time it was invented) but simplifies the rasterization code and permits multiple passes.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Memory is now faster and more plentiful, and a z-buffer is almost always used for real-time rendering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A drawback of the basic z-buffer algorithm is that each pixel ends up either entirely covered by a single object or filled with the background color, causing jagged edges in the final image.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early *anti-aliasing* approaches addressed this by detecting when a pixel is partially covered by a shape, and calculating the covered area.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The A-buffer (and other supersampling and multi-sampling techniques) solve the problem less precisely but with higher performance.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time 3D graphics, it has become common to use complicated heuristics (and even neural-networks) to perform anti-aliasing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In 3D rasterization, color is usually determined by a *pixel shader* or *fragment shader*, a small program that is run for each pixel.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Until relatively recently, Pixar used rasterization for rendering its animated films.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Unlike the renderers commonly used for real-time graphics, the Reyes rendering system in Pixar's RenderMan software was optimized for rendering very small (pixel-sized) polygons, and incorporated stochastic sampling techniques more typically associated with ray tracing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the simplest ways to render a 3D scene is to test if a ray starting at the viewpoint (the "eye" or "camera") intersects any of the geometric shapes in the scene, repeating this test using a different ray direction for each pixel.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This method, called *ray casting*, was important in early computer graphics, and is a fundamental building block for more advanced algorithms.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render shapes defined by *constructive solid geometry* (CSG) operations.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early ray casting experiments include the work of Arthur Appel in the 1960s.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Appel rendered shadows by casting an additional ray from each visible surface point towards a light source.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] He also tried rendering the density of illumination by casting random rays from the light source towards the object and plotting the intersection points (similar to the later technique called *photon mapping*).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When rendering scenes containing many objects, testing the intersection of a ray with every object becomes very expensive.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Special data structures are used to speed up this process by allowing large numbers of objects to be excluded quickly (such as objects behind the camera).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These structures are analogous to database indexes for finding the relevant objects.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The most common are the *bounding volume hierarchy* (BVH), which stores a pre-computed bounding box or sphere for each branch of a tree of objects, and the *k-d tree* which recursively divides space into two parts.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs include hardware acceleration for BVH intersection tests.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] K-d trees are a special case of *binary space partitioning*, which was frequently used in early computer graphics (it can also generate a rasterization order for the painter's algorithm).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Octrees*, another historically popular technique, are still often used for volumetric data.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Geometric formulas are sufficient for finding the intersection of a ray with shapes like spheres, polygons, and polyhedra, but for most curved surfaces there is no analytic solution, or the intersection is difficult to compute accurately using limited precision floating point numbers.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Root-finding algorithms such as Newton's method can sometimes be used.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To avoid these complications, curved surfaces are often approximated as meshes of triangles.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Volume rendering (e.g. rendering clouds and smoke), and some surfaces such as fractals, may require ray marching instead of basic ray casting.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render an image by tracing light rays backwards from a simulated camera.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After finding a point on a surface where a ray originated, another ray is traced towards the light source to determine if anything is casting a shadow on that point.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If there are multiple light sources, brightness contributions of the lights are added together.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For color images, calculations are repeated for multiple wavelengths of light (e.g. red, green, and blue).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing usually performs anti-aliasing by taking the average of multiple samples for each pixel.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It may also use multiple samples for effects like depth of field and motion blur.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If evenly spaced ray directions or times are used for each of these features, many rays are required, and some aliasing will remain.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Cook-style*, *stochastic*, or *Monte Carlo ray tracing* avoids this problem by using random sampling instead of evenly spaced samples.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of ray tracing is commonly called *distributed ray tracing*, or *distribution ray tracing* because it samples rays from probability distributions.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Distribution ray tracing can also render realistic "soft" shadows from large lights by using a random sample of points on the light when testing for shadowing, and it can simulate chromatic aberration by sampling multiple wavelengths from the spectrum of light.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real surface materials reflect small amounts of light in almost every direction because they have small (or microscopic) bumps and grooves.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A distribution ray tracer can simulate this by sampling possible ray directions, which allows rendering blurry reflections from glossy and metallic surfaces.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, if this procedure is repeated recursively to simulate realistic indirect lighting, and if more than one sample is taken at each surface point, the tree of rays quickly becomes huge.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Another kind of ray tracing, called *path tracing*, handles indirect light more efficiently, avoiding branching, and ensures that the distribution of all possible paths from a light source to the camera is sampled in an unbiased way.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing was often used for rendering reflections in animated films, until path tracing became standard for film rendering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Films such as Shrek 2 and Monsters University also used distribution ray tracing or path tracing to precompute indirect illumination for a scene or frame prior to rendering it using rasterization.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advances in GPU technology have made real-time ray tracing possible in games, although it is currently almost always used in combination with rasterization.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This enables visual effects that are difficult with only rasterization, including reflection from curved surfaces and interreflective objects, and shadows that are accurate over a wide range of distances and surface orientations.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing support is included in recent versions of the graphics APIs used by games, such as DirectX, Metal, and Vulkan.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing has been used to render simulated black holes, and the appearance of objects moving at close to the speed of light, by taking spacetime curvature and relativistic effects into account during light ray simulation.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity (named after the radiometric quantity of the same name) is a method for rendering objects illuminated by light bouncing off rough or matte surfaces.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of illumination is called *indirect light*, *environment lighting*, *diffuse lighting*, or *diffuse interreflection*, and the problem of rendering it realistically is called *global illumination*.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization and basic forms of ray tracing (other than distribution ray tracing and path tracing) can only roughly approximate indirect light, e.g. by adding a uniform "ambient" lighting amount chosen by the artist.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity techniques are also suited to rendering scenes with *area lights* such as rectangular fluorescent lighting panels, which are difficult for rasterization and traditional ray tracing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the original radiosity method (first proposed in 1984) now called *classical radiosity*, surfaces and lights in the scene are split into pieces called *patches*, a process called *meshing* (this step makes it a finite element method).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The rendering code must then determine what fraction of the light being emitted or diffusely reflected (scattered) by each patch is received by each other patch.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These fractions are called *form factors* or *view factors* (first used in engineering to model radiative heat transfer).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The form factors are multiplied by the albedo of the receiving surface and put in a matrix.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The lighting in the scene can then be expressed as a matrix equation (or equivalently a system of linear equations) that can be solved by methods from linear algebra.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Solving the radiosity equation gives the total amount of light emitted and reflected by each patch, which is divided by area to get a value called *radiosity* that can be used when rasterizing or ray tracing to determine the color of pixels corresponding to visible parts of the patch.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time rendering, this value (or more commonly the irradiance, which does not depend on local surface albedo) can be pre-computed and stored in a texture (called an *irradiance map*) or stored as vertex data for 3D models.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This feature was used in architectural visualization software to allow real-time walk-throughs of a building interior after computing the lighting.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The large size of the matrices used in classical radiosity (the square of the number of patches) causes problems for realistic scenes.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Practical implementations may use Jacobi or Gauss-Seidel iterations, which is equivalent (at least in the Jacobi case) to simulating the propagation of light one bounce at a time until the amount of light remaining (not yet absorbed by surfaces) is insignificant.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Form factors may be recomputed when they are needed, to avoid storing a complete matrix in memory.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The quality of rendering is often determined by the size of the patches, e.g. very fine meshes are needed to depict the edges of shadows accurately.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important improvement is *hierarchical radiosity*, which uses a coarser mesh (larger patches) for simulating the transfer of light between surfaces that are far away from one another, and adaptively sub-divides the patches as needed.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This allows radiosity to be used for much larger and more complex scenes.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Alternative and extended versions of the radiosity method support non-Lambertian surfaces, such as glossy surfaces and mirrors, and sometimes use volumes or "clusters" of objects as well as surface patches.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Simplified and partially precomputed versions of radiosity are widely used for real-time rendering, combined with techniques such as *octree radiosity* that store approximations of the light field.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As part of the approach known as *physically based rendering*, **path tracing** has become the dominant technique for rendering realistic scenes, including effects for movies.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For example, the popular open source 3D software Blender uses path tracing in its Cycles renderer.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Like *distributed ray tracing*, path tracing is a kind of *stochastic* or *randomized* ray tracing that uses Monte Carlo or Quasi-Monte Carlo integration.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was proposed and named in 1986 by Jim Kajiya in the same paper as the rendering equation.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Kajiya suggested reducing the noise present in the output images by using *stratified sampling* and *importance sampling* for making random decisions such as choosing which ray to follow at each step of a path.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Even with these techniques, path tracing would not have been practical for film rendering, using computers available at the time, because the computational cost of generating enough samples to reduce variance to an acceptable level was too high.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Monster House, the first feature film rendered entirely using path tracing, was not released until 20 years later.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In its basic form, path tracing is inefficient (requiring too many samples) for rendering caustics and scenes where light enters indirectly through narrow spaces.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Attempts were made to address these weaknesses in the 1990s.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Metropolis light transport* samples paths by modifying paths that were previously traced, spending more time exploring paths that are similar to other "bright" paths, which increases the chance of discovering even brighter paths.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Multiple importance sampling* provides a way to reduce variance when combining samples from more than one sampling method, particularly when some samples are much noisier than the others.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This later work was summarized and expanded upon in Eric Veach's 1997 PhD thesis, which helped raise interest in path tracing in the computer graphics community.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The Arnold renderer, first released in 1998, proved that path tracing was practical for rendering frames for films, and that there was a demand for unbiased and physically based rendering in the film industry; other commercial and open source path tracing renderers began appearing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Computational cost was addressed by rapid advances in CPU and cluster performance.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing's relative simplicity and its nature as a Monte Carlo method (sampling hundreds or thousands of paths per pixel) have made it attractive to implement on a GPU, especially on recent GPUs that support ray tracing acceleration technology such as Nvidia's RTX and OptiX.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport are more difficult to implement efficiently on a GPU.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Techniques have been developed to denoise the output of path tracing, reducing the number of paths required to achieve acceptable quality, at the risk of losing some detail or introducing small-scale artifacts that are more objectionable than noise.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks are now widely used for this purpose.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Research into improving path tracing continues.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Many variations of bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport have been explored, and ways of combining path tracing with photon mapping.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent *path guiding* approaches construct approximations of the light field probability distribution in each volume of space, so paths can be sampled more effectively.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] By combining denoising and hardware ray tracing acceleration, it is now practical to use path tracing for real-time rendering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to performance constraints, biased techniques such as a radiance cache may be incorporated.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Spatiotemporal reservoir resampling (ReSTIR) aims to improve the quality of real-time path tracing and allow more complex lighting by reusing samples (paths) from previous frames and adjacent pixels.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As of 2003, machine learning (ML) techniques were being used in other areas of computer graphics, such as texture synthesis, fitting surfaces to point clouds, and fitting curves to motion capture data.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The use of ML for rendering expanded with the availability of GPUs that can evaluate neural networks (especially convolutional neural networks) quickly.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks and Gaussian mixture models have been used in conjunction with rendering techniques such as path tracing to encode bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs), or to encode cached radiance at points in space (for biased acceleration of rendering or for path guiding).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural radiance fields (NeRFs) take the latter approach to an extreme, encoding radiance at all points in a volume, and using evaluation of this approximation as the primary rendering method.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the most widely used applications of machine learning in rendering is denoising of path traced images (in practice, most path tracing now likely uses such a denoiser).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Denoisers specialized for real-time rendering can work with very low sample counts and improve temporal coherence to reduce flickering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering is usually limited by available computing power and memory bandwidth, and so specialized hardware has been developed to speed it up ("accelerate" it), particularly for real-time rendering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware features such as a framebuffer for raster graphics are required to display the output of rendering smoothly in real time.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware acceleration does not replace the use of software for rendering, rather it speeds up selected operations or calculations using dedicated circuits, or runs portions of the software's code on a different type of processor.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the era of vector monitors (also called *calligraphic displays*), a display processing unit (DPU) was a dedicated CPU or coprocessor that maintained a list of visual elements and redrew them continuously on the screen by controlling an electron beam.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advanced DPUs such as Evans & Sutherland's Line Drawing System-1 (and later models produced into the 1980s) incorporated 3D coordinate transformation features to accelerate rendering of wire-frame images.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Evans & Sutherland also made the Digistar planetarium projection system, which was a vector display that could render both stars and wire-frame graphics (the vector-based Digistar and Digistar II were used in many planetariums, and a few may still be in operation).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A Digistar prototype was used for rendering 3D star fields for the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan – some of the first 3D computer graphics sequences ever seen in a feature film.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Shaded 3D graphics rendering in the 1970s and early 1980s was usually implemented on general-purpose computers, such as the PDP-10 used by researchers at the University of Utah.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was difficult to speed up using specialized hardware because it involves a pipeline of complex steps, requiring data addressing, decision-making, and computation capabilities typically only provided by CPUs (although dedicated circuits for speeding up particular operations were proposed ).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Supercomputers or specially designed multi-CPU computers or clusters were sometimes used for ray tracing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Clark and Marc Hannah designed the Geometry Engine, a VLSI chip for performing some of the steps of the 3D rasterization pipeline, and started the company Silicon Graphics (SGI) to commercialize this technology.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Home computers and game consoles in the 1980s contained graphics coprocessors that were capable of scrolling and filling areas of the display, and drawing sprites and lines, though they were not useful for rendering realistic images.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Towards the end of the 1980s PC graphics cards and arcade games with 3D rendering acceleration began to appear, and in the 1990s such technology became commonplace.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Today, even low-power mobile processors typically incorporate 3D graphics acceleration features.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The 3D graphics accelerators of the 1990s evolved into modern GPUs.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] GPUs are general-purpose processors, like CPUs, but they are designed for tasks that can be broken into many small, similar, mostly independent sub-tasks (such as rendering individual pixels) and performed in parallel.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to their origins, GPUs typically still provide specialized hardware acceleration for some steps of a traditional 3D rasterization pipeline, including hidden surface removal using a z-buffer, and texture mapping with mipmaps, but these features are no longer always used.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs have features to accelerate finding the intersections of rays with a bounding volume hierarchy, to help speed up all variants of ray tracing and path tracing, as well as neural network acceleration features sometimes useful for rendering.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering algorithms will run efficiently on a GPU only if they can be implemented using small groups of threads that perform mostly the same operations.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As an example of code that meets this requirement: when rendering a small square of pixels in a simple ray-traced image, all threads will likely be intersecting rays with the same object and performing the same lighting computations.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For performance and architectural reasons, GPUs run groups of around 16-64 threads called *warps* or *wavefronts* in lock-step (all threads in the group are executing the same instructions at the same time).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If not all threads in the group need to run particular blocks of code (due to conditions) then some threads will be idle, or the results of their computations will be discarded, causing degraded performance.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, the term *hardware rendering* (possibly an abbreviation of "hardware accelerated rendering" or "hardware-assisted rendering") was sometimes used to mean rendering using a hardware-accelerated rasterization pipeline (typically for real-time rendering).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In contrast, *software rendering* meant offline rendering using software that was not limited by the capabilities of graphics hardware, and could use more realistic and higher quality techniques.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Both hardware and software have evolved, and although these terms are still used, their meaning may now be context-dependent.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When OpenGL and Direct3D were introduced in the 1990s, there was a need to use these APIs on computers that did not have hardware acceleration for 3D graphics.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] "Fallback" rendering implementations were provided that did not require special hardware, and these are sometimes called "software renderers" (today hardware acceleration is almost always available, and these CPU-only implementations are used primarily for testing).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] More recently, "software rendering" may also mean rendering that does not use graphics APIs such as OpenGL, Metal, Direct3D, or Vulkan.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Types of renderers that in the past might have been called "software renderers" (e.g. path tracing renderers used for offline rendering for movies) now commonly use GPU acceleration, often via APIs such as CUDA or OpenCL, which are not graphics-specific.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Since these latter APIs allow running C++ code on a GPU, it is now possible to run the same rendering code on either a CPU or GPU.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The following is a rough timeline of frequently mentioned rendering techniques, including areas of current research.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that even in cases where an idea was named in a specific paper, there were almost always multiple researchers or teams working in the same area (including earlier related work).
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When a method is first proposed it is often very inefficient, and it takes additional research and practical efforts to turn it into a useful technique.
[src:volumetric-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The list focuses on academic research and does not include hardware.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] In scientific visualization and computer graphics, **volume rendering** is a set of techniques used to display a 2D projection of a 3D discretely sampled data set, typically a 3D scalar field.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] A typical 3D data set is a group of 2D slice images acquired by a CT, MRI, or MicroCT scanner.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Usually these are acquired in a regular pattern (e.g., one slice for each millimeter of depth) and usually have a regular number of image pixels in a regular pattern.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] This is an example of a regular volumetric grid, with each volume element, or voxel represented by a single value that is obtained by sampling the immediate area surrounding the voxel.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] To render a 2D projection of the 3D data set, one first needs to define a camera in space relative to the volume.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Also, one needs to define the opacity and color of every voxel.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] This is usually defined using an RGBA (for red, green, blue, alpha) transfer function that defines the RGBA value for every possible voxel value.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] For example, a volume may be viewed by extracting isosurfaces (surfaces of equal values) from the volume and rendering them as polygonal meshes or by rendering the volume directly as a block of data.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The marching cubes algorithm is a common technique for extracting an isosurface from volume data.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Direct volume rendering is a computationally intensive task that may be performed in several ways.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Another method of volume rendering is Ray marching, a category of 3D computer graphics rendering techniques in which rays are traced step by step, subdividing each ray into smaller segments and sampling a function at each interval.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Volume rendering is distinguished from thin slice tomography presentations, and is also generally distinguished from projections of 3D models, including maximum intensity projection.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Still, technically, all volume renderings become projections when viewed on a 2-dimensional display, making the distinction between projections and volume renderings a bit vague.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Nevertheless, the epitomes of volume rendering models feature a mix of for example coloring and shading in order to create realistic and/or observable representations.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] A direct volume renderer requires every sample value to be mapped to opacity and a color.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] This is done with a "transfer function" which can be a simple ramp, a piecewise linear function or an arbitrary table.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Once converted to an RGBA color model (for red, green, blue, alpha) value, the composed RGBA result is projected on the corresponding pixel of the frame buffer.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The way this is done depends on the rendering technique.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] A combination of these techniques is possible.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] For instance, a shear warp implementation could use texturing hardware to draw the aligned slices in the off-screen buffer.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The technique of volume ray casting can be derived directly from the rendering equation.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] It provides results of very high quality, usually considered to provide the best image quality.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Volume ray casting is classified as image based volume rendering technique, as the computation emanates from the output image, not the input volume data as is the case with object based techniques.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] In this technique, a ray is generated for each desired image pixel.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Using a simple camera model, the ray starts at the center of projection of the camera (usually the eye point) and passes through the image pixel on the imaginary image plane floating in between the camera and the volume to be rendered.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The ray is clipped by the boundaries of the volume in order to save time.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Then the ray is sampled at regular or adaptive intervals throughout the volume.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The data is interpolated at each sample point, the transfer function applied to form an RGBA sample, the sample is composited onto the accumulated RGBA of the ray, and the process repeated until the ray exits the volume.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The RGBA color is converted to an RGB color and deposited in the corresponding image pixel.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The process is repeated for every pixel on the screen to form the completed image.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] This is a technique which trades quality for speed.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Here, every volume element is splatted, as Lee Westover said, like a snow ball, on to the viewing surface in back to front order.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] These splats are rendered as disks whose properties (color and transparency) vary diametrically in normal (Gaussian) manner.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Flat disks and those with other kinds of property distribution are also used depending on the application.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The shear warp approach to volume rendering was developed by Cameron and Undrill, popularized by Philippe Lacroute and Marc Levoy.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] In this technique, the viewing transformation is transformed such that the nearest face of the volume becomes axis aligned with an off-screen image data buffer with a fixed scale of voxels to pixels.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The volume is then rendered into this buffer using the far more favorable memory alignment and fixed scaling and blending factors.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Once all slices of the volume have been rendered, the buffer is then warped into the desired orientation and scaled in the displayed image.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] This technique is relatively fast in software at the cost of less accurate sampling and potentially worse image quality compared to ray casting.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] There is memory overhead for storing multiple copies of the volume, for the ability to have near axis aligned volumes.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] This overhead can be mitigated using run-length encoding.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Many 3D graphics systems use texture mapping to apply images, or textures, to geometric objects.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Commodity PC graphics cards are fast at texturing and can efficiently render slices of a 3D volume, with real time interaction capabilities.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Workstation GPUs are even faster, and are the basis for much of the production volume visualization used in medical imaging, oil and gas, and other markets (2007).
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] In earlier years, dedicated 3D texture mapping systems were used on graphics systems such as Silicon Graphics InfiniteReality, HP Visualize FX graphics accelerator, and others.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] This technique was first described by Bill Hibbard and Dave Santek.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] These slices can either be aligned with the volume and rendered at an angle to the viewer, or aligned with the viewing plane and sampled from unaligned slices through the volume.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Graphics hardware support for 3D textures is needed for the second technique.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Volume aligned texturing produces images of reasonable quality.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The image quality degrades with coarse slice counts, though there is often a noticeable transition when the volume is rotated.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Due to the extremely parallel nature of direct volume rendering, special purpose volume rendering hardware was a rich research topic before GPU volume rendering became fast enough.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The most widely cited technology was the VolumePro real-time ray-casting system, developed by Hanspeter Pfister and scientists at Mitsubishi Electric Research Laboratories, which used high memory bandwidth and brute force to render using the ray casting algorithm.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The technology was transferred to TeraRecon, Inc. and two generations of ASICs were produced and sold.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Pixel shaders are able to read and write randomly from video memory and perform some basic mathematical and logical calculations.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] These SIMD processors were used to perform general calculations such as rendering polygons and signal processing.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] In recent GPU generations, the pixel shaders now are able to function as MIMD processors (now able to independently branch) utilizing up to 1 GB of texture memory with floating point formats.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] With such power, virtually any algorithm with steps that can be performed in parallel, such as volume ray casting or tomographic reconstruction, can be performed with tremendous acceleration.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The programmable pixel shaders can be used to simulate variations in the characteristics of lighting, shadow, reflection, emissive color and so forth.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Such simulations can be written using high level shading languages.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The primary goal of optimization is to skip as much of the volume as possible.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] A typical medical data set can be 1 GB in size.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] To render that at 30 frame/s requires an extremely fast memory bus.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Skipping voxels means less information needs to be processed.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Often, a volume rendering system will have a system for identifying regions of the volume containing no visible material.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] This information can be used to avoid rendering these transparent regions.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] This is a technique used when the volume is rendered in front to back order.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] For a ray through a pixel, once sufficient dense material has been encountered, further samples will make no significant contribution to the pixel and so may be neglected.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The use of hierarchical structures such as octree and BSP-tree could be very helpful for both compression of volume data and speed optimization of volumetric ray casting process.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Image segmentation is a manual or automatic procedure that can be used to section out large portions of the volume that one considers uninteresting before rendering, the amount of calculations that have to be made by ray casting or texture blending can be significantly reduced.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] This reduction can be as much as from O(n) to O(log n) for n sequentially indexed voxels.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Volume segmentation also has significant performance benefits for other ray tracing algorithms.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Volume segmentation can subsequently be used to highlight or expose structures of interest.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] By representing less interesting regions of the volume in a coarser resolution, the data input overhead can be reduced.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] On closer observation, the data in these regions can be populated either by reading from memory or disk, or by interpolation.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The coarser resolution volume is resampled to a smaller size in the same way as a 2D mipmap image is created from the original.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] These smaller volume are also used by themselves while rotating the volume to a new orientation.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Pre-integrated volume rendering is a method that can reduce sampling artifacts by pre-computing much of the required data.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] It is especially useful in hardware-accelerated applications because it improves quality without a large performance impact.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Unlike most other optimizations, this does not skip voxels.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Rather it reduces the number of samples needed to accurately display a region of voxels.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] The idea is to render the intervals between the samples instead of the samples themselves.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] This technique captures rapidly changing material, for example the transition from muscle to bone with much less computation.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Image-based meshing is the automated process of creating computer models from 3D image data (such as MRI, CT, Industrial CT or microtomography) for computational analysis and design, e.g.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] For a complete display view, only one voxel per pixel (the front one) is required to be shown (although more can be used for smoothing the image), if animation is needed, the front voxels to be shown can be cached and their location relative to the camera can be recalculated as it moves.
[src:volumetric-rendering/volume-rendering] Where display voxels become too far apart to cover all the pixels, new front voxels can be found by ray casting or similar, and where two voxels are in one pixel, the front one can be kept.
